&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;&lt;cite&gt;photo / &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.flickr.com/photos/suzanneandsimon&quot;&gt;suzanneandsimon&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href=&quot;http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/files/licensing/bluebg/cc_by.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Creative Commons licensed: Attribution 2.0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/cite&gt; Referred to as hop vine, hops is actually a &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bine_%28botany%29&quot;&gt;bine&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Ten years ago some farmers couldn&amp;#8217;t give hops away to beer brewers. Several years of overproduction had left the hops market saturated with supply and short on buyers. Today that couldn&amp;#8217;t be further from the truth. Over the next few years beer enthusiasts around the world may be feeling the pinch on both their palates and their pocketbooks.&lt;/p&gt;

